LAGOS – Former Delta state governor, Chief James Onanefe Ibori has mourned the passage of late Professor Grace Alele-Williams, the first female Nigerian to obtain a doctorate degree and first female vice-chancellor in Nigeria who died on Friday at the age of 89. The late Alele- Williams, a professor of Mathematics was the Vice-chancellor of the University of Benin (UNIBEN) at a time young Ibori was also a student there. Professor Alele Williams was appointed the vice-chancellor of the University of Benin in 1985 by the regime of former Military President, Ibrahim Babangida. Her tenure witnessed a drastic reduction in cultism, a menace in UNIBEN at the time.Prof Alele Williams who was schooled in Nigeria and the United States speaking on her appointment as the first female vice-chancellor of a Nigerian university said it was a test case to demonstrate a woman’s executive capability. In his tribute, Ibori who mourned her with a deep sense of personal loss said the late Alele-Williams was an outstanding woman of integrity. “Alele -Williams’ life imparted greatly on mine as she was the Vice-Chancellor of the University of Benin while I was a student there. I remember her as an outstanding woman of integrity and one of those who showed my feet the way to follow”.“I regret her passing even as I thank God for the pace-setting life she lived as a high -achiever,” Ibori said following the news that Alele Williams has died.